15 WHEREAS, Georgia's Quick Start job training program has positioned it as a national leader
16 in workforce policies that strengthen upward mobility for impoverished families; and
17 WHEREAS, new independent research from the Sutherland Institute identifies evidence of
18 families receiving public assistance feeling disincentivized from pursuing or accepting
19 opportunities to increase their earned income and improve their financial situation; and
20 WHEREAS, this research finds that 77 percent of respondents to a statewide survey of public
21 assistance recipients report concern that earning additional income would result in a loss of
22 benefits that would worsen their family's financial situation; and
23 WHEREAS, this research further finds that 62 percent of respondents report feeling stuck
24 in a low-income job due to the belief that increased income would cause loss of benefits that
25 would not be worth the additional income; and
26 WHEREAS, this research further finds that 43 percent of respondents report having
27 intentionally limited their earned income due to fear of triggering a "benefits cliff" or
28 "benefits plateau"; and
29 WHEREAS, the Georgia Center for Opportunity has produced a computational model
30 demonstrating the effects of benefits cliffs in every Georgia county via their website,
31 benefitscliffs.org; and
32 WHEREAS, the Federal Reserve Bank of Atlanta defines this phenomenon as a wage
33 increase that "may result in a family being financially worse off (a benefits cliff) or no better
34 off (a benefits plateau) than before the wage increase"; and
