35 WHEREAS, for families who strive to improve their economic conditions, benefits cliffs,
36 benefits plateaus, and other disincentive effects have the potential to trap families in poverty
37 by hindering workforce participation and disincentivizing financial stability; and
38 WHEREAS, the State of Georgia is committed to finding innovative solutions to any
39 disincentive effects to work, family formation, economic independence, or other
40 opportunities that may be present in the social safety net; and
41 WHEREAS, due to federal restrictions, states have limited authority to experiment with
42 federally funded social safety net programs for the purpose of finding innovative reforms that
43 can address benefits cliffs, benefits plateaus, perception gaps, or other obstacles to upward
44 mobility experienced by families receiving public assistance.
45 NOW, THEREFORE, BE IT RESOLVED BY THE HOUSE OF REPRESENTATIVES that
46 the members of this body urge the President of the United States and Congress to grant
47 additional flexibility and autonomy to states to experiment with innovative pilot programs
48 and other reforms to improve social safety net programs by addressing any work
49 disincentives that may exist.
50 BE IT FURTHER RESOLVED that the members of this body urge the President and
51 Congress to expedite waiver approvals for states pursuing innovative pilot programs or other
52 reforms to the social safety net.
53 BE IT FURTHER RESOLVED that the members of this body urge the President and
54 Congress to pursue additional flexibility to the states in the form of block grants for a wider
55 array of existing social safety net programs.
